    <div class="exercise">
        <span class="exercise-type practice">Practice</span>
        <h4>Fallacy Spotting in the Wild</h4>
        <p>Find a political speech, op-ed, or advertisement and identify at least three fallacies. For each one, name the fallacy, explain why it's fallacious in this context, and consider whether the argument's conclusion might still be true despite the flawed reasoning. Notice when the boundary between legitimate argument and fallacy is unclear.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
        <span class="exercise-type challenge">Challenge</span>
        <h4>Steelman a Fallacious Argument</h4>
        <p>Take one of the fallacies you identified in the previous exercise and try to construct a non-fallacious argument for the same conclusion. What evidence would you need? What premises would have to be established? If you can't find a good argument for the conclusion, consider whether the conclusion itself might be flawed.</p>
